IBM (International Business Machines) was founded in New York a hundred years ago and is the original name of the Computing Tabulation Recording Corporation.
The name IBM was adopted in 1924 – it was originally a brand used in the branches of Canada and South America.
The basis for the birth of IBM comes from the merger of four companies dating back to the 1880s.
It had inventions such as the famous "slide clock", which allows to control the entry and exit of employees.
The architect of the new company was the businessman Charles Ranlett Flint, who also chaired his supervisory board until 1930.
Flint hired the head of a competition company, Thomas J. Watson, to help him with the company's management.
The new leader eclipsed IBM’s founder (Watson’s ideas remain the firm foundation on which corporate culture and identity are sustained).
