How Travel Prices Have Evolved Since 1989
Until 1989 there were only five authorized state travel agencies in Czechoslovakia: <0xC4><0x8C>edok, Sporturist, CKM, Recrea and Autoturist.
Travel agencies at the time sold travel only to the socialist bloc in most cases, as travel to the West was very restricted.
Czech tourists therefore went on holiday to the beaches of the DDR (German Democratic Republic), the Soviet Union, (Sochi in Crimea in the Black Sea) to Bulgaria and Romania (both in the Black Sea) and Hungary (Balaton).
A positive exception was the period between 1962 and 1972, when one could travel to Yugoslavia, however, after the Yugoslav regime inclined to the west and the travels of Czech tourists were then quite restricted.
A great paradox of socialism was the fact that the citizens of the socialist bloc (i.e., also Czechoslovakians) were not allowed to travel freely and individually, not even through the socialist countries.
If a citizen wanted to travel individually, for example, to Poland or the Soviet Union, he needed an invitation letter, if not, individual travel was not possible.
Travel agencies also offered trips to the West at the time, but one had to get in the queue with a sleeping bag and spend the whole night, or have “good friends” at the agency.
Still, not everything was won.
The so-called “promise of change” that was the condition for travel to the West, was not granted to the “politically unreliable people” who could not travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not a freely convertible currency and, without a guarantee of exchange, it was not possible to obtain the resources (the Western currency) to travel to the West.
The vast majority of Czechs spent their holidays in their own country, so there was a large number of cottages and summer houses, which the Czechs acquired.
The Czech way of travel has undergone a genuine revolution since 1989.
While until 1989 for us it was the one no longer going to spend holidays in the DPRK or Bulgaria, last year the Czechs made 4.5 million vacation trips to countries around the world.
There is a great paradox, of which today we are no longer aware, the fact that to the currently favorite destination, Croatia, it was not possible to travel freely until 1989, because it was part of Yugoslavia then.
In the early 1990s visa exemption was imposed for travel to the neighbouring states of Western Europe, resulting in a huge wave of short-term visits, especially to Vienna or Germany.
The Czechoslovaks, for a long time, did not see themselves tired of the excursions to the West, everyone wanted to see it at least for a moment.
For example, in Paris, Czech groups slept in parks in tents, as our then income did not allow us to pay a hotel or pension.
A typical feature of the Czechs of that time was to bring food (conserved, embedded, etc.) to save.
Another important moment was the introduction of the convertibility of the Czech crown, so our tourists could finally, after decades, freely buy Western currency.
Our standard of living was increasing and with it average wages were also rising, which caused an increase in travel demand around 1997.
With the increase in the demand for travel, agencies began to regularly prepare travel using charter flight connections from 1997 onwards, which made travel prices incredibly low compared to the past, thanks to the possibility of obtaining discounts for the volume of passengers.
By the end of the 90s, the Czechs were already travelling visa-free to almost all developed countries except the US, which made our travels even easier.
Another interesting moment in the history of post-revolutionary tourism occurred already in 2000, when it was organized, thanks to a huge demand, the first direct flight from the Czech Republic to an exotic country, and went to Thailand.
Since that year, direct flights depart every year with Czech tourists making distant and hot countries. This winter will be flying directly from the Czech Republic to 12 exotic destinations.
The exotic countries currently visit about 100,000 Czechs a year.
Another interesting moment of this era, symbolizing our post-revolutionary development, came in 2008.
On November 17, 2008, the U.S. removed visas for Czech tourists, making our country one of the most developed countries in the world.
In 2008, the Czechs, for the first time in their history, spent more than half of their holiday abroad (50.3%) and for the first time in their history, spent more than 15,000 Czech crowns per head on trips abroad, including on-site expenses.
