When watching the tour, they have come delivering huge shows with many songs.
What have you planned for your presentation in Costa Rica?
As we’ve never played there before, then we have no restrictions on what we can do.
We will try to give the best show possible with a good variety of songs; we will try to play a couple of songs from each album and give our fans a good and diverse repertoire.
You never repeat the repertoire.
What's the reason for this?
I think it’s partly because we have nine records and we can play more than 120 songs and everyone likes different songs, so it’s hard to choose which songs to play every night.
When we have two or three songs in the repertoire that we’ve been not playing for a while, that keeps us focused and also keeps us surprised because it reminds us of the reasons we liked those songs and that we might have forgotten.
That makes the show more interesting for us and therefore I think it also makes it more interesting for people.
With this tour, they are celebrating 20 years of trajectory.
Looking back, is it hard to believe everything they have achieved?
Yes, absolutely.
“First of all, I think none of us imagine that we would be in a big rock band and have done it for more than 20 years to make it look like a dream.
We continue to count our blessings and we are very excited that we can continue to make music together.
We all love and love creating music.
We are fortunate to go to places in the world that we have always wanted to go.
Things couldn't be better for us.
What did it mean for you to have been a fundamental part of the emergence of the grunge?
It has always been an honor to be part of that group of big bands.
We are very friendly to the people of Soundgarden, Mudhoney and Alice in Chains.
It is surprising when a movement arises from a group of friends and is something uncommon.
Occasionally, a band from a city emerges, but it’s much weirder when five or ten bands come out of the same city at the same time.
We are proud and honored to be part of the Seattle group.
We still play with some of them from time to time.
Last year, we were at a festival with Alice in Chains and we were in Canada with Mudhoney, we saw Soundgarden on his tour, so we’re lucky to be friends with all of them still and we’re honored to be part of that Seattle sound that came up.
It is also very strange that a band like yours stays united and with the same members for so long.
Yes, four of us have been together for 21 years and Matt (Cameron) joined us 13 years ago, which alone is much longer than many bands last.
Firstly, I think we are all lucky to be still alive, and secondly, we all care about the others.
We are all very close friends and, thanks to that, musical avenues have also opened that give each one the freedom to experiment.
We trust each other with each other’s music and it couldn’t be better.
Your relationship with the word fame has not been simple; however, thanks to your success, you have been able to do whatever you want.
How do you find a balance?
As we have grown, it has been easier to find a balance.
We make sure you’re not too busy because it’s easy to fall into that game of big crowds and people who love your music.
While one remembers that people are there for music, that reminds you that you have to respect the music and what it brought, without behaving about being famous and being a rock star, something that none of us really care about.
How do you remember your other Mother Love Bone project?
I think we wrote very good songs and at first it was great.
We were a band for almost three years and we never released a record until after Andy (Andrew Woods) died.
There was a lot of frustration because it lasted so long and the most important thing is that we are still very friends with Bruce (Fairweather) and Greg (Gilmore), who started the band with us and when I hear a song or see a picture I think about the incredible person Andy was and how he made me laugh, it was always a pleasure to go and work.
He was an amazing human being and we missed him.
The national band Las Robertas will be in charge of opening the show in Costa Rica.
Is it true that you know your job, especially Eddie Vedder, and that's why you chose it for the opening?
Yes, the production sent us videos with several proposals and that was the band we liked the most, so we’re looking forward to seeing what Las Robertas can offer live and should be very entertaining.
Why do they always change the lyrics of Yellow Ledbetter live?
That's a question for Ed (Eddie Vedder), so I don't know.
He sings it and I think he does it with the first thing that happens to him.
As a bassist, what are your influences?
There are so many.
Among the first things that happen to me are Geezer Butler, John Entwistle, C. J. Ramone, John Doe, Paul McCartney, Chuck Dukowski...
There are so many that I could talk all afternoon about the bassists that I love.
How has Pearl Jam managed to keep grunge relevant even though it is no longer a fashion?
I think we all always feel a little disconnected from the word grunge.
When I think about it, it reminds me of the bands I mentioned before, like Mudhoney, Soundgarden, Nirvana and all that emerged at the same time, and, if there is relevance now, I think it’s something wonderful because it’s music worth listening and bands like Mudhoney are doing better music now than ever.
At first, his music had darker content and now it has become more positive.
What is this change due to?
It’s interesting because I think there are a couple of songs on the new album that may seem lighter, but there are also songs like The End or Just Breathe that qualify as very dark songs although they may sound a bit positive.
With both of them, when Ed played them to me, I cried when I heard them and they are deeply dark songs.
I think when you grow up and there’s some trauma in your life and you lose a family member or a friend, those things start to influence your art and your music, and those two songs, undoubtedly, represent that to me.
Also, I think you can be a happy person and still be able to make music that is dark.
