Secretary Dionisio Pérez Jácome gives details of the air crash where the Secretary of Government, Francisco Blake, and seven more people died
The Secretariat of Communications and Transportation (SCT) reported that the results thrown on the crash where the Secretary of Government, Francisco Blake Mora, and seven others died, indicate that the helicopter was directly impacted on the ground in full structural integrity, without the pilot being able to attempt landing.
During a press conference, Dionisio Pérez Jácome, Secretary of Communications and Transport, mentioned that before taking off the aircraft, the pilot found that the weather conditions were appropriate for flying.
"The elements that seem to indicate that the unit had several contacts with the ground, the ashs had contact with trees at 25 meters where the unit lost the fuselage."
He also reported that the unit was designed for 19 people, so it had the necessary requirements to transport staff.
In addition, he said that the investigations carried out in the impact area did not report the appearance of pieces on the ground.
“In a search, there are no parts or components of the ship elsewhere, the impact was presented structurally.
"The design of the helicopter was for 19 passengers, it had adequate requirements for transporting passengers.
The terrain has a slope of seven degrees at 30 degrees of inclination.
At the moment, the secretary assured that it is a priority to have the results as soon as possible; however, the research can last several months, it could even reach a year.
Gilberto López Meyer, Director General of Airports and Auxiliary Services, said that at the time of the impact, the Presidential Major State helicopter was operating at cruise speed and that this happened on a soft ascent terrain.
"This information strengthens the hypothesis of a normal cruise operation at the time of the impact," he said.
At the press conference, the head of the SCT, Pérez Jácome, listed six relevant elements in the research:
Visual flight:
According to aeronautical normativity the flight was performed under the visual flight rules, this implies that the crew must have visibility during the flight and on the ground.
Meteorological conditions:
Reports at the AICM located suitable conditions for takeoff, as the aircraft progressed towards the border area between the DF and the State of Mexico presenting low-altitude cloud layers.
Selected routes:
Due to cloud conditions, the crew is likely to have searched for a less elevated area and more visibility towards the Cuernavaca Valley.
Location of the impact.
The impact coordinates and the last radar aircraft registration coincide, probably before the impact there was no loss of control or alteration in the flight trajectory.
Dispersion of aircraft residues in a reduced area:
The information available so far suggests that the impact occurred in a straight and sided trajectory.
The aircraft's residue dispersion pattern allows to assume that the helicopter was impacted on the ground under conditions of structural integrity.
No evidence of fire or explosion has been detected:
At the scene of the accident, no evidence remains on the remains of the ship of some kind of explosion or fire.
The latest results of the research indicate that there may have been multiple contacts with the field.
During field work, parts of the aircraft have been found at an elevation of 9,200 feet above average sea level, the terrain presents a slope ranging from seven degrees to 30 degrees of inclination.
The photographs show the sequence in which it was predictably disarticulated along said route.
The information provides elements that seem to indicate that the helicopter may have had multiple impacts on the ground.
After a thorough search in a wider area than the agreed site, around the accident, no scattered parts of the aircraft have been found, which reinforces the presumption that the impact was presented under conditions of structural integrity.
MSS Announces Protocol to Find Obesity Gene
Leads Social Security research to discover the obesity gene in children and young people; it is supported by IPN specialists
The Mexican Institute of Social Security (IMSS) has announced that it is conducting research to discover the obesity gene in children and young people, called the ‘Childhood and Adolescent Obesity Genes’ protocol, which will allow for markers associated with overweight.
In a statement, the head of the Medical Research Unit in Biochemistry of the Hospital of Specialties of the 21st Century National Medical Center, Miguel Cruz López, explained that a multidisciplinary team of doctors, nurses, nutritionists and social workers was integrated.
The team is supported by specialists and graduate students of the National Institute of Public Health (INSP) and the Center for Advanced Research and Studies (Cinvestav) of the National Polytechnic Institute (IPN).
The research invites the population, whether or not right-occupied, to attend the participating sports units of the IMSS in the Valle de México, where the tests are carried out to minors, every Saturday from 8:00 p.m.
He pointed out that the protocol began in the Cuauhtémoc Sports Unit (State of West Mexico) and that since October 8, the activity is carried out in the Nezahualcóyolt Sports Unit (State of East Mexico).
Once the goal of gathering 500 or 600 minors is met, the study will continue in the Sport Unit Independencia (south of the Federal District) and finally in the Sport Unit Morelos (north of the Federal District).
He explained that the purpose of this research is to know the components and the importance of genetics with respect to the development of obesity and to identify risk factors in children and young Mexicans to prevent the onset of chronic degenerative diseases.
In celebrating World Diabetes Day on November 14, he stated that the goal is to bring together 3,000 children and young people between the ages of six and 14, with the consent and supervision of their parents, for the implementation of specific food questionnaires.
They will also be asked about physical activity and family history of diseases, in order to avoid risk factors that trigger conditions such as diabetes or kidney failure.
He detailed that on Saturdays all participants were applied anthropometric measurements (weight, size, waist circumference), blood pressure measurements, determination of glucose, triglycerides, cholesterol and insulin levels, and genetics (it is sought to identify genes associated with child obesity).
Cruz López noted that this research responds to concerns of health professionals about the alarming weight gain in minors.
“The health surveys of 1999 and 2006 noted that in just six years, there was an increase, in the case of boys, of 77 percent in obesity, and in girls of 47 percent; in terms of overweight, a dramatic increase was also observed,” the IMSS specialist said.
He pointed out that the justification for the search for markers is that the population of the country differs from others by their genetic history.
On average, the Mexican has 65 percent Native American heritage, 30 percent European and five percent African, and this condition is reflected in the genes associated with diabetes and overweight.
He explained that in general, the genetics of obesity translates into the inability to burn the excess energy we consume (calories) and that it is stored in the form of fat.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit for participants is the comprehensive evaluation of children, allowing them to detect whether they have any degree of overweight or obesity.
He even said the presence of dark-colored folds (acantosis) in the neck and forearm, indicating the likelihood of metabolic alterations and even prediabetes.
The information is handled confidentially, the doctors deliver it in writing to the parents, who are explained each of the measurements and lifestyle changes they must make to prevent diseases.
Cruz López explained that there are three main components that cause overweight, obesity and other chronic illnesses: sedentaryism, which is the lack of daily physical activity, staying sitting in front of the TV most of the day and using means of transport instead of walking short distances.
