UNAM's asphalt would avoid bumps
Rafael Herrera, researcher at UNAM’s Faculty of Chemistry, develops polymer-modified asphalts to produce a mixture with better performance, regardless of environmental and temperature conditions
If the signals sent to the pavement were met, it would not be necessary to repair about 200,000 beaks each rainy season in the Metropolitan Zone of the Valley of Mexico, warned Rafael Herrera Nájera, researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry (FQ) of UNAM, who could be assured that even if the construction process is complete, and the construction process could be eliminated.
In its conference A Technological Opinion of the Buckets, dictated in the framework of the International Year of Chemistry, announced that the laboratory in charge of the bucket develops asphalt modified with polymers to produce a mixture with characteristics similar to those of the asphalt, but with greater mechanical resistance, both at high and low temperatures.
Herrera Nájera estimated that this type of modified asphalt could be used in places where the weather is extremely hot, such as some cities in the north of the country, to improve its performance and hence the formation of buds.
He explained that asphalt, the heaviest part of oil, is a set of hydrocarbon molecules, some of high molecular weight, called asphalts, and others of low molecular weight, called maltenes, that together give the floor its characteristic viscoelastic behavior.
The viscoelastic behavior of the asphalt consists in that at high temperatures, near 180 degrees, it behaves like a liquid, at 120 degrees Celsius its viscosity is very high and at 50 degrees Celsius it has a near solid state, while at very low temperatures, the asphalt becomes broken, he added.
The above means that in the streets the resistance of asphalt is not uniform, but is being modified during the day according to environmental and temperature conditions, the chemical engineering specialist warned.
The FQ researcher noted that the streets of Mexico City are mostly covered by flexible flooring, which consists of six layers of materials, the last three of which involve asphalt.
Among the most superficial layers is the asphalt folder, consisting of small stones bathed in asphalt and then compacted.
Each of the stones that make up the folder, he pointed out, is bathed with asphalt.
By transiting the vehicles and generating effort, it allows the forces to spread very well on the floor.
If it were modified asphalt they would spread even better, the chemical engineer said.
On the asphalt, plentiful, is placed a last layer called rolling folder, which is made of a fine stone material, i.e., a sand that is also bathed in asphalt.
As this is the layer that will be in contact with the tires of the vehicles, it must have more mechanical strength than the asphalt folder and provide friction on the road.
Being the part of the floor that will receive and disseminate the efforts, the rolling folder also requires having the proper thickness and the material from which it is made should be taken care.
Climate, especially humidity and temperature variations, are also a very important factor to consider, especially water, he said, because it significantly affects the performance of the asphalt folder.
When the soil is moistened, the water diffuses into the interior of the folder and it is difficult for it to come out, this causes a smoothing of all the layers of the floor and thus the formation of buds.
In the process of forming a beam, he said, the first to wear is the bearing film and only then the asphalt folder is affected, but the damage does not occur instantly, but is a process that should be addressed to the first signals with appropriate maintenance programs.
The also member of the National System of Investigators explained that vehicle load is another important factor in the formation of buckets, and therefore the thickness of each floor layer should always be in relation to vehicle load and ensure that it meets, in order to prevent buckets from forming frequently.
Rafael Herrera warned that there is still a lot to research and work on asphalt, for example, asphalt emulsions, which in other countries are already found even on the market and allow to repair buckets easily and without the need to use high temperatures.
