Energy policy:
Facts must be worth more than dogmas.
If there is an issue that you can’t deal with considering short-term considerations or simply thinking about emotions, it’s energy policy.
The availability and cost of electricity directly influence the purchasing power and the competitiveness of companies.
It is appropriate that an electoral meeting should be the time to reflect on such issues and on the place of nuclear energy.
The debate will only be useful if it examines the overall economic, social and environmental implications of the proposed options.
The French must base their opinion on objective facts, on rational data.
Now that we are 7 billion people on the planet, demographic evolution will double electricity demand by 2050, unless a huge part of the world’s population is deprived of a vital element.
At the same time, the growing scarcity of fossil resources will have to be mitigated to continue producing electricity continuously, without forgetting the imperative need to reduce greenhouse gas emissions to fight climate change, a topic that has disappeared from the ecological debate.
The Fukushima accident does not change any of these parameters.
Therefore, Germany remains alone in its decision to give up nuclear energy.
That is not the case neither with Belgium, which subordinates its own to the need to find a source capable of replacing it, nor with Switzerland, which only aims to build state-of-the-art power plants.
On the other hand, the United Kingdom, Finland, Poland, the Czech Republic, the Netherlands, Sweden, South Africa, China, India and Brazil, to name a few examples, move forward with determination with their projects.
The United States, for its part, after Fukushima decided to add a unit to its park, resuming the construction of a power plant interrupted after the Three Mile Island accident.
If the German model, based on renewable energies, is sometimes presented as an example, reality goes against such discourse.
The choice of Berlin will mean a sharpening of the price of electricity, a greater energy dependence on the increased need for imported gas, in particular from Russia, an increase in CO2 emissions from the construction of gas and coal plants.
Within a few months, the adverse effects will be noticed.
We must meditate on the case of Denmark.
Champion of Europe in the wind sector, of which it receives 30% of its electricity, is also one of the major users of coal and gas due to wind intermittentness; for this reason, its CO2 emissions and the price of its electricity are, respectively, 65% and 50% higher than the European average.
On the contrary, thanks to the constancy of our energy policy, our neighbours pay for an electricity bill 40% higher than that of French households.
While in a globalized economy the cost of energy is a key driver of competitiveness and a guarantee of the maintenance of industrial utility in the national territory, French companies benefit from the cheapest electricity in Europe.
For that reason, any significant reduction in nuclear energy would mean a sharp rise in electricity prices, which would remain realistic to the wonderful statements about the reindustrialization of our country and the defense of our purchasing power.
This is a price that the vast majority of French people refuse to pay and, in fact, do not, in principle, oppose that type of energy, according to surveys.
Let us remember that our country’s energy policy has lost building an industrial sector with 125,000 executive jobs and 410,000 indirect jobs.
Widely export-oriented, it encompasses a galaxy of SMEs specializing in international markets that can create non-displaceable jobs.
If France decided to abandon nuclear energy, it would involve the sacrifice of a large part of those SMEs and the loss of 6 billion euros per year in French exports of nuclear equipment and services.
Which electrician would charge an EPR designed to run for sixty years, when its manufacturer is expected to collapse?
To solve the nuclear energy equation, one must admit that there is no miraculous source of electricity production, just as there is no diabolical source.
Areva’s development of low-carbon, nuclear and renewable solutions demonstrates the complementarity of energy sources.
In the case of nuclear energy, it is essential to maintain the highest level of safety.
In France, we have a security authority that exercises strict and transparent control over both the existing power plants and the construction of Flamanville.
Our teams, of renowned professionalism, are also obsessed with safety.
In the middle of the century, the nuclear sector has suffered three serious accidents.
Only one, the Three Mile Island, occurred under normal operating conditions; it did not have any consequences for people or the environment.
In Chernobyl, the accident was due to the design of the reactor and unforgivable human failures.
In Fukushima, some people seem to forget that the accident was due to two natural disasters of unprecedented scope, which caused the deaths of tens of thousands of people.
The nuclear sector will learn from this accident, as it did from the previous two.
Thanks to these advances and cooperation between the security authorities, and French and German operators and builders, the EPR has a design capable of resisting such phenomena.
As all electric players who want to build a power plant are studying it, the interruption of their construction in Flamanville would be a great gift for Areva and EDF competitors, as it would leave them free to take the lead in the inevitable development of the nuclear sector.
It is indispensable and legitimate to seek the best energy options for our country, but it would be irresponsible to let the emotion, dogmas and maneuvers of Partisan dominate such an important debate for the economic, social and financial situation of our country.
