The question is that, on this subject, there is quite a consensus between the left and the right.
In the case of the right, Jacques Chirac set the orientation stating in 1976 that "900,000 unemployed should not be a problem for a country that has about two million immigrant workers", while on the left, the tone set by Michel Rocard explaining that France "cannot take over all the misery of the world" in 1990.
The only difference, the degree of generosity
In 2005, both the left and the right shared the fear of invading the national territory by a multitude of Polish fountains.
On both sides, immigrants are considered a burden to the French economy and society.
The only difference is the degree of generosity with which they act towards immigrants.
