This idea of immigration as a burden, a problem, may turn out to be economically profitable, but economically comes out very expensive.
As economists Ian Goldin and Geoffrey Cameron point out in a recent work that summarizes the most recent knowledge on immigration (Exceptional People: How Migration Shaped Our World and Will Define Our Future, May 2011, Princeton University Press, 352 pp.), there is a broad consensus among the migrants and the impact on the positives among the countries.
The restriction of immigration weakens growth and damages employment.
Fears related to the impact of immigrants are based on the idea that they can replace national workers, particularly under-skilled workers, by pressuring them to reduce their wages.
