Some may have believed that, for democracy to finally triumph over its enemies, it would be enough to exercise the vote and in the most direct manner possible.
We know, since Napoleon "The Little One", that this was something thought.
The universal suffrage, although it is a necessary condition for democracy, is not enough on its own and can even become an "instrument of oppression", as the Republican philosopher Etienne Vacherot used to say.
No, democracy requires much more: a public space, a public spirit, values, an organization, a separation and control of powers, an education, lights, economic and social solidarity, justice.
The crisis we are experiencing in Europe is an economic crisis, but it is about to become a political and democratic crisis.
The palinody of the true-false Greek referendum had, in this regard, a double revealing effect: it showed the need for a powerful return of the political sphere, but also the worrying sense of its impossibility, of its inconsistency.
You have to think about this ambivalence to overcome it.
The truth is that the front lines of the democratic battle have now shifted and that, in many cases, Republican soldiers are no longer advancing in the right direction.
We will not win if we demand a succession of national referendums, organized according to needs and disorderly.
A blank signature to the absolute European monarch or a void of the nationalist hole: what options for the citizen!
No, we do not want to take effective blows, but a common exercise of full right, calm and continuous, of options and democracy, this time on a European scale.
There is no crisis in Greece, Italy, Spain, Portugal (in fact, we would not know where the list ends), because there is only one crisis, the crisis of Europe.
The whole of Europe is the one that clings to the orders of the markets and rating agencies, the one that suffers from its impotence and its lack of solidarity.
It is the whole of Europe that suffers humiliation in the international sphere.
We are concerned about transferring sovereignty to Europe, but it is the whole of Europe that slowly loses sovereignty and, with it, each of its nations.
The most urgent thing is that popular sovereignty will regain the grip of the European project.
Because only together will Europeans be able to reduce the weight of their debts, free themselves from the markets and prepare their future through investments.
Outcome from the crisis will require decisions at European level that cannot be taken without full democratic legitimacy, unless it is to lead us to disaster.
Having long struggled against this proposal by the Socialists and by Jacques Delors, everyone is now calling for European economic governance.
Let it be so.
But to think about it without greater political and democratic integration, and without being lived as such by the citizens, would be a new madness and would lead us to a new deadlock.
We must take on a new stage of European construction.
To build the Republic in France, it was necessary to “make” Republicans.
A revolution motivated by interests would not be enough.
This lesson is still applicable.
We must build a more integrated Europe from an economic point of view.
Only by building a more democratic Europe on the political level can it be achieved, a true European people's sovereignty.
To build Europe, let’s make Europeans.
Cards with "contactless" chips are generalized
The world chip card show starts Tuesday in Villepinte, near Paris, with an optimistic atmosphere.
In fact, the year 2011 is expected to end with an increase of 11% in global sales of microprocessor cards (bank cards, SIM phones, etc.), with a total of 6 billion units, according to Eurosmart’s estimates.
The most powerful segment is contactless technology, which allows you to pay for public transportation or purchases simply by approaching the card to a reader.
This year, 460 million contactless chip cards will be sold worldwide, 320 million more than the previous year!
Its share is expected to continue to increase in 2012 (580 million units are projected) and account for about 10% of the world market for chip cards (6,925 million cards).
Europe, which has long been reluctant with respect to the Asia-Pacific region, is gaining ground in the contactless payments sector.
Approximately 26 million Visa bank cards already have this feature, which is accepted in 75,000 payment terminals.
In France, its beginnings are more modest: 400,000 contactless Visa cards are being used.
But the large surfaces work for four.
Carrefour has issued 2.5 million contactless MasterCard Pass cards this year.
In order to get the upper hand, however, it is necessary for banks to make them available to their customers.
“There are two large French establishments that have committed to systematically disseminating contactless bank cards among their customers in the future,” said Gérard Nébouy, Managing Director of Visa Europe France.
Banks Test Payment by Mobile Phone
But it is only a first step towards the payment method of the future: the mobile phone.
Currently, there are few devices equipped with NFC (Near Field Communication) technology, which is essential for making transactions.
"They're waking up."
“But I should finally experience a real boom next year.”
“We expect between 80 and 120 million units to be sold worldwide in 2012,” explains Marc Bertin, president of Eurosmart.
But the banks take the lead.
Crédit agricole bank announced yesterday the launch of a test between December and June in Caen.
Approximately 200 customers and partners’ iPhones will be paired with a fund that allows contactless payment.
BPCE has a similar project in Strasbourg and Marseille.
And the Société Générale has also stated yesterday that it is preparing the marketing of an offer that allows its customers to pay contactlessly via their mobile.
From the Sahara to Nigeria, the terrorist front is on the rise
Paris is concerned about the links between Al Qaeda in the Islamic Maghreb and the Boko Haram sect.
Links between the Al Qaeda terrorist group in the Islamic Maghreb (Aqmi) and the Nigerian Boko Haram sect, which has long been suspected, have been confirmed.
On Sunday, the Algerian Deputy Foreign Minister, Abdelkader Messahel, even claimed that Alger "has the certainty".
"The way both organizations operate and intelligence services reports show they are cooperating," he said, without giving further details.
Paris seems to come to a similar conclusion.
The investigation into the kidnapping of two Frenchmen in Niger last January would have resumed the passageways.
Kidnapped at a restaurant in Niamey by people related to Aqmi, Antoine de Léocour and Vincent Delory died the next day along with several of their kidnappers during an operation launched by the French special forces.
In the rubble of the intervention, French and Nigerian investigators discovered several phone chips belonging to the terrorists.
I'm a terrorist
The study of the calls made indicates to several interlocutors based in Mali, Niger and Nigeria.
According to Radio France Internationale (RFI), two figures have caught the attention of researchers: one leads to a Nigerian who stayed for a long time in Maiduguri, a city in northern Nigeria, the cradle of Boko Haram, and the other to a man who is allegedly close to Aqmi and the sect.
“This is progress, but we must certainly expect to have more formal evidence before we talk about operational cooperation between Aqmi and Boko Haram.”
"But it is possible."
