The Nord Stream, the new gateway to Russian gas in Europe
The Nord Stream pipeline, which directly connects Western Europe with Russia through the bottom of the Baltic Sea, has already been put into service.
It must supply gas to meet the needs of 30 million households.
Gazprom, the Russian gas giant, has wanted to celebrate the event with great pomp.
Last Tuesday, more than 500 guests, including four Heads of State and Government, participated on the shores of the Baltic, between the music of the orchestra and a delicate buffet, at the inauguration of the Nord Stream, the new pipeline that communicates directly, under the sea, Russia with Germany.
Symbolically, German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitry Medvedev, French Prime Minister François Fillon and his Dutch counterpart Mark Rutte have turned together the steering wheel of the valve that controls Russian gas input into the Western Europe network.
With this new pipeline, an additional 27.5 million cubic meters of Russian gas will reach western Europe each year through a 1,224-kilometre first pipeline that connects the St. Petersburg region with the Land of Mecklenburg-Pomerania.
A second pipeline is expected to be completed by the end of 2012, which will provide a total of 55 billion cubic meters of gas, i.e. enough to cover all French consumption.
In addition, there is already talk of the possibility of building a third pipe along the same route.
For Gazprom, the timely completion of this huge work presents airs of victory.
Poland and the Baltic States had strongly opposed the project.
In fact, the Nord Stream will allow gas to be supplied directly to Germany, avoiding the land flow by third countries (Poland and Ukraine).
Suddenly, these two countries lose some of their power: for them, it will be harder to influence Russia by threatening to shut it down to Western European markets.
At the height of the debate, Warsaw did not hesitate to compare the Nord Stream as a "new German-Soviet pact", in reference to the Hitler-Stalin alliance to occupy Poland in 1939.
That is, if the topic is politically delicate.
Western Europe, by supporting the Russian project, has gained greater security of supply.
But the price is a weakening of Europe's energy, since the project has created a gap between Eastern and Western Europeans.
In just five years, Russia has succeeded in its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and the rich Western countries, large gas consumers and with increasingly limited reserves.
“This pipeline is a component of our association with Russia, a new artery that binds us organically,” François Fillon said during the inauguration of the pipeline, demonstrating to what extent the major contracts in the gas sector are as political as well as economic.
All this explains the wide smiles on the faces of Gazprom’s managers, numerous at Lubmin, at the point of arrival of the gas.
The construction of this pipeline is also a technical achievement.
The submarine tube is made of cement-coated steel to protect it from ship anchors.
It is supported at the bottom of the sea, at an average of 200 m depth.
To build it, it was necessary to avoid minefields dating from World War II.
“It was necessary to remove or destroy a hundred of them, by precaution,” said Jens Müller, a spokesman for Nord Stream.
It was also necessary to take extreme measures to protect fauna and flora.
The tube is a long metal serpent that weighs as much as 242 Eiffel towers and is not interrupted throughout its length: neither by valves, nor by maintenance stations.
A control platform was planned in the waters of Sweden, but the project managers renounced it when they saw that the Swedes were not very willing to allow a Russian state society to be established permanently at sea off their coasts.
“In case of failure, we will interrupt the passage of gas in less than a minute,” said Jens Müller.
In case of leakage, the gas from the pipeline will therefore be released into the atmosphere.
But builders consider it unlikely that a leak will occur, as they have foreseen joints that, according to forecasts, will have a leak every 100,000 years.
Control of the state of the pipeline is ensured by a submarine robot, drawn by a ship, carrying out external inspections, as well as by a device circulating inside the pipeline.
With the form of a pure, it is introduced into the interior of the tube, which has a diameter of one meter, and moves with the gas.
Upon arrival, after three full days of travel at a speed of three meters per second, it provides accurate data on possible metal deformations.
The gas pipeline has been designed to operate for fifty years without the need for any kind of repair.
The circulation of the gas is simply guaranteed by the pressure.
At first it is 200 bars and at the output of 100 bars.
Five companies have joined forces to be able to carry out this project.
The leading company is Gazprom, which owns 51% of the shares.
The Germans E.ON and BASF (15.5% each), as well as the Dutch Gasunie and the French group GDF Suez (9% each).
These five companies have created a joint venture called Nord Stream, which is responsible for the construction and operation of the pipeline.
It is based in Zug, Switzerland, where taxation is particularly favourable.
Afterwards, Gazprom rented to the company, for a renewable period of twenty-five years, all of its gas transport capacities.
“Gazprom will pay for the total capacity, regardless of the amount of gas that is actually transported,” said Jens Müller.
Funding for the construction of the pipeline has been completed by 30% with the contribution of shareholders and by 70% through bank loans.
The total cost of the work should reach <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>7.4 billion for the two pipes.
For GDF Suez, for example, the investment has reached 240 million.
But minority shareholders are confident that they will not exceed their investment, as Gazprom assumes the risk of spending alone.
The gas pipeline emerges from the Baltic Sea in Lubmin, on a sandy coast planted with pine trees.
Valves, with a height of 4.5 meters, form the gas exit door.
There are sensors that measure the pressure, temperature and specific characteristics of the gas upon arrival, before it is transferred to the German pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, the terminal receives one million cubic meters of Russian gas every hour.
At total capacity, it will be three million per hour and in 2012, six million.
Moleskine, a branded booklet.
Created half a century ago by an Italian company, Moleskine wants to return people the taste for writing.
It has an air of adventure, hours of writing in the light of a candle.
The Moleskine booklet is easily recognized, with its black rectangular pastes, its rubber, its broken white leaves, as ageing over time.
However, Moleskine booklets with the current look were born... in 1997.
The Italian company Modo Modo, based in Milan, decided at the time to launch a design notebook, but distinguished.
Maria Sebregondi, then consultant for the company, was responsible for the launch of the new product.
The booklet is inspired by an ancient production technique, the soft skin, which refers to a varnish cotton that was used, among other things, to cover the banquets.
This type of book was highly valued by writers and travelers.
“Moleskine has adapted to the present taste an old and forgotten object, an icon of avant-garde artists until the 20th century,” says Maria Sebregondi, who has since become responsible for the brand in Mode Mode.
And he achieved success.
Between 2006 and 2010, sales increased by 26%, to a volume of 12.7 million units sold.
The confidential production of the first years, in which only 3,000 books were designed, has remained a long way off.
Moleskine goes beyond the Italian borders and exports its products to 70 countries, from France to the United States.
It is difficult to determine the profile of the buyer, as the notebook attracts both businessmen as well as students and professionals.
Like Moleskine, its users are cosmopolitan, open-minded and cultist.
The small Italian company, which had twelve employees at its beginnings, now owns about 100 and, since 2008, has two offices: one in Milan and the other in New York.
He distributes his notebooks in bookstores, from the Fnac to the small shops in the city centre, and has been able to impose his identity.
“We have adapted to the times and the need to write, despite the boom of emails,” explains Maria Sebregondi.
This cultural firm goes hand in hand with the development of Moleskine: recently, the brand has launched the exhibition "Detour" where architects or artists exhibit their own notebook.
In August, he also released a notebook with leopard caps, on the occasion of the Locarno Film Festival.
Taking advantage of its success and this cultural aura, Moleskine has been able to diversify its products: bags, calendars, pens, computer cases... The brand encompasses a wide range of supports.
An enviable success: in the fall of 2006, Mode Mode was acquired by the investment fund SG Capital Europe, now Syntegra Capital, writing a new page in Moleskine’s history.
Why is the unemployment rate of disabled workers still so high?
About 19% of people with disabilities are looking for a job.
The 15th Week for the Employment of the Disabled begins today.
Despite a well-established public policy, applied since 2005, the unemployment rate among people with disabilities doubles the average rate: 19%, compared to 9% for the general population.
Detachable?
“No,” says Éric Blanchet, Managing Director of Adapt, the association that organizes the week for the employment of disabled people.
“The progress achieved over the past 15 years is considerable.
“At the time, the unemployment rate was not twice but three times higher than the average.
"However, there is still a lot to do."
It should be noted that the unemployed with disabilities continue to face numerous barriers to access to employment.
They usually have a more advanced age: 37% are over 50 years old (average 17%).
They have a low level of qualification: 80% have not completed their bachelor’s degree and, out of the 2.3 million students in higher education, only 10,000 are disabled.
Finally, long-term unemployment is very widespread among them: 53% for the disabled, compared to 38% on average.
That is, there are numerous issues that make it particularly difficult to return to the workplace and that “constitute the quid of the problem,” says Christian Grapin, CEO of Tremplin, an association created in 1992 to help companies hire disabled workers.
These are the objective obstacles.
In addition, there are those that are not mentioned; people’s mentality is advancing, but too slowly.
A study conducted in April by the IMS-Entreprendre association for the Cité noted that the directors surveyed had "a low level of knowledge about disabilities," with "excessive representation of people in wheelchairs, physically or intellectually disabled."
The result: private companies with more than 20 workers are far from the goal of hiring 6% of disabled workers, a goal set in a 1987 law.
According to the latest available figures, dating back to 2008, they reached a ratio of 2.6%.
“We are now reaching around 3%,” says Pierre Blanc, CEO of Agefiph, the agency responsible for collecting contributions from companies that do not comply with this law.
The test: the number of establishments "subject to this contribution", as well as the amounts spent, have decreased between 2007 and 2011, from 59,000 to 46,000 structures (and from 606 to 480 million euros).
“The 2005 law, which increased contributions, has generated a lot of pressure for companies,” explains Pierre Blanc.
“But this improvement also reflects true awareness, particularly among large groups.”
According to the Ministry of Labour, only 59% of companies with between 20 and 49 employees have disabled employees in their workforce, compared with 82% of companies with between 100 and 199 employees.
